<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate pipe friction loss?", answer: "Use the Hazen-Williams equation for water: hf = 4.52 × Q^1.852 / (C^1.852 × d^4.87), where hf is head loss per foot of pipe, Q is flow in gpm, C is the pipe's roughness coefficient, and d is the inside diameter in inches. Multiply by pipe length to get total head loss, then convert to psi using 1 ft of water = 0.4331 psi." },
  { question: "What is the C-factor for common pipe materials?", answer: "PVC and PEX have C = 150 (smoothest). New copper is 140. New steel is 120. Old galvanized is 100. Old cast iron is 100. A higher C means less friction loss for the same flow and pipe size. The C-factor also drops over time as mineral deposits build up on the inside of the pipe." },
  { question: "What is a safe water velocity for pipes?", answer: "Keep cold water velocity under 8 ft/s (2.4 m/s) and hot water under 5 ft/s to prevent erosion corrosion, water hammer, and noise. Very high velocities can carve channels in copper pipe over years. Quick formula: v (ft/s) = 0.4085 × gpm ÷ d² (inches). The calculator shows velocity and flags if it exceeds 8 ft/s." },
  { question: "Why does pipe size matter so much?", answer: "Friction loss goes up with the 4.87th power of the inverse of diameter. Cutting diameter in half increases friction loss by about 30×. A 1/2\" pipe carrying 10 gpm loses about 28 psi per 100 ft; a 3/4\" pipe carries the same flow with about 6 psi loss per 100 ft. Always upsize long runs — bigger pipe is cheap compared to pump or pressure boost equipment." },
  { question: "Does hot water flow differently than cold?", answer: "Slightly. Hot water has lower viscosity and density, so friction loss drops by about 5-10% compared to cold water at the same flow. The calculator assumes cold water (60 °F) as the standard design basis. For hot water, treat the result as a conservative upper bound." }
]) %>

